            <p>Get the greatest offers on business tickets for Air Canada by visiting Faresmatch Bookings right now! For passengers seeking a more efficient and pleasant journey—both at the airport and on board—the Air Canada business class experience is well worth the price and is a fitting reflection of the airline's standing as the most well-known in Canada. Depending on the time of day and availability, Air Canada provides its distinctive business class experience on some domestic routes as well as on foreign flights. </p>
            <p>Longer-haul flights on the Boeing 777, Boeing 787, and A330-300 aircraft provide the finest business class suites (Signature Service to differentiate it from shorter-haul business class). On the A220-300, Air Canada also has business class seats, but you won't get the privacy of a lie-flat bed or pod.</p>

            <h2>All the benefits of Air Canada Business class </h2>

            <p><b>Check-in </b></p>
            <p>At major airports, passengers traveling in <b>Air Canada business class</b> have access to special lanes that provide quicker security screenings for eligible Air Canada Elite members, as well as customers traveling in Business Class, Signature Class, and Premium Rouge (in Canada, the US, and a few Sun destinations). In 33 airports worldwide, Super Elite members and Air Canada Signature Class passengers also enjoy individualized and committed concierge services. </p>
            <p><b>Baggage </b></p>
            <p>Two 50-pound checked baggage are free of charge for business class passengers. Priority luggage services are another perk of business class tickets that speed up the baggage claim and check-in processes. Priority bags have unique tags attached to them, meaning qualifying Air Canada Elite members and passengers traveling in Business Class, Premium Economy Class, Signature Class, and Premium Rouge will see their luggage on the carousel first. </p>
            <p><b>Lounge access </b></p>
            <p>The Air Canada Signature Suite, Air Canada Café, and Air Canada Maple Leaf Lounge are the three types of lounges that Air Canada offers. Aeroplan Elite members and all business class tickets get access to lounges. Conveniently situated near Air Canada's domestic gates at Toronto Pearson International Airport is the Air Canada Café. With 23 lounges spread over 16 airports, the standard Air Canada Maple Leaf Lounges are the most well-liked lounge both domestically and internationally. An open bar with wine, beer, and cocktails, as well as fresh and packaged meals.</p>
            <p><b>Meals </b></p>
            <p>Travelers in business class on Air Canada can choose from a variety of seasonal delicacies depending on their location, including creations by renowned Canadian chef David Hawksworth. The supper consists of three courses served simultaneously, with unique dishes like lamb or salmon tartare paired with grilled vegetables and a crisp salad. To guarantee their favorite option will be available on board, passengers who follow a plant-based diet or have specific meal demands should be sure to book them as early as possible—at least 24 hours in advance. </p>
            <p><b>Alcohol </b></p>
            <p>On flights offering lunch or dinner, business class customers can choose from an excellent wine list featuring some of the world's best wineries, such as Gerard Bertrand and Drappier Champagne House. Additionally, a selection of domestic beer, hard liquor, and cocktails are available to passengers. </p>

            <h3>Variants of Air Canada business class flights </h3>

            <h6>Boeing 777</h6>
            <p> All Boeing 777 business class aircraft include forty seats with lie-flat beds, pneumatic cushion adjustments, head, and neck massaging headrests, and touchscreen entertainment systems with noise-canceling headphones included.</p>
            <h6>Boeing 787</h6>
            <p>The business class experience on the Boeing 787 fleet is almost the same as that of the 777, right down to the practical 1-2-1 arrangement. There are just thirty seats available on this aircraft, though.</p>
            <h6>A330-300</h6>
            <p>This aircraft has 27 business class seats in a 1-2-1 arrangement. For customers traveling with a companion, the arrangement provides a movable privacy divider between adjacent business-class seats.</p>
            <h6>A220-300</h6>
            <p>Rather than having lie-flat beds or pods, the A220-300 has twelve roomy reclining seats spread out over three rows in a 2-2 arrangement. Across Canada, this aircraft primarily serves short-haul and regional Air Canada flights.</p>

